  "prompt": "How long can a human being survive without sleep?",
  "response": "The duration a human can survive without sleep varies significantly among individuals, but total sleep deprivation for extended periods can be extremely harmful and potentially life-threatening. Controlled experiments have shown that staying awake for 24 to 48 hours can significantly impair cognitive and motor functions, including memory, judgment, and coordination.\n\nOne of the most famous cases is that of Randy Gardner, who in 1965 set a record for voluntarily staying awake for approximately 264 hours (11 days). Gardner experienced significant cognitive and physical symptoms, including mood swings, hallucinations, and severe memory lapses.\n\nWhile this case did not result in permanent harm, continual sleep deprivation can lead to serious health issues, including weakened immune function, hormonal imbalances, heart disease, and potentially death. Animal studies suggest that prolonged sleep deprivation can be fatal, evidenced by experiments where rats deprived of sleep died after approximately two weeks.\n\nThus, while it is difficult to pinpoint the exact timeframe for humans, consistent and long-term sleep deprivation is undoubtedly dangerous and should be avoided.",
